itting uncomfortably within the law and of disputed value. Shining a new light on English legal history, Justice and mercy reveals the moral dilemmas created by the establishment of the common law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian ethicsxHistory of doctrinesyMiddle Ages, 600-1500. 0aJustice, Administration ofzEnglandxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aJustice, Administration ofzGreat BritainxHistory. 0aLaw and ethics. 0aLawzGreat BritainxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aMercy. 0aScholasticismzEngland. 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aCommon Law.  aEngland.  aJudges.  aJudgment.  aJustice.  aMercy.  aScholasticism.  aTheology.  aTwelfth century.  aTwelfth-Century Renaissance.  alaw.1 aByrne, Philippa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packagez978311128277040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612535440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526125354423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526125354/original  a978-3-11-128277-0  Manchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packageb2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles